0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Overview</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6.5pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Overall, we consider the new approach to tax policy making has been implemented well and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">l</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">argely meeting its objectives. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Howe</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ver, w</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e do consider that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">there is room for improvement.  I have set out below a summary of the key themes we are seeing and this is followed</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> by some more detailed examples:</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6.5pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The process works best when there is a clear explanation of the policy intent at </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the start;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In some cases the policy approach does not seem to be followed as there is no or little consultation;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Where there is a consultation process, sometimes the consultation timetable does not allow business sufficient time to respond;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Where legis</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">lation is to be subject to a substantial rewrite</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> (such as the loan relationship rules) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> it would be helpful if the rewrite is not timed to coincide with other significant changes (such as the GAAP conversion deadline)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">;</span></p><p style="margin:13pt 0pt 13pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In many case, the consultation seems </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to progress in a satisfactory manner but at the end there is a rush to get legislation drafted in time for the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Finance B</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ill. This often results in badly drafted legislation which then has to be “corrected” in guidance notes;</span></p><p style="margin:13pt 0pt 13pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Where</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> substantial changes to ne</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">eds to be made during the consultation process it may be better start the drafting afresh rather than trying to adapt what has already been prepared.</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6.5pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Examples</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6.5pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Life a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">ssurance tax regime</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6.5pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">An example of good practice where the new approach was followed was the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> development of the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">new </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">life a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ssurance tax regime. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In our view, the consultation was seen as a success by both Industry and HMRC\Treasury. The project was delivered on time, the legislation is more straightforward and the overall regime simpler than the fo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">rmer</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Points of difference were, mostly, resolved in a way that was mutually agreed. </span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6.5pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Some of the reasons for the success are:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17.85pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">There was a time limit on the consultation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and a clear need for new legislation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">due to the expected implementation of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> S</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">olvency </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">II</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">  This was recognised by both i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ndustry and HMRC\Treasury so that solutions had to be found.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17.85pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The consultation was well led and managed by Andy Stewardson</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> who stayed with it until the end and was assiduous in consulting on all relevant matters</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">  Represent</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">atives from insurance groups, industry bodies and advisers contributed their knowledge and expertise to the process and as a result the final outcome was widely seen as acceptable</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and workable</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 13pt 17.85pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The life assurance industry is fairly small in terms of numbe</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">rs of firms and most tax directors know each other already, as well as know</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">HMRC </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ustomer </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">R</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">elationship </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">M</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">anager</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> (obviously that is not something which Government policy can influence)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">  This meant that there was a focussed group with a largely commo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">n purpose.</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6.5pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">However, despite being viewed by us as a success, there were still some issues</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> identified with the consultation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17.85pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Small firms were not directly represented and relied on advisers and it was difficult to get their input</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> HMRC should </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">find a way of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">seek</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ing input from all affected taxpayers</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17.85pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In a number of cases we were told that it was too late </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to change the drafting</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, even as early as January 2012</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.  If there is a genuine consultation, this needs to be better managed. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 13pt 17.85pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Due to the complexity and scope </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">of the legislation, t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">he burden on clients (and advisers)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">of participating in the consultation </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">should not be underestimated.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">  The process should not be started unless there is a clear need and well understood policy intention.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6.5pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Banking Levy</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6.5pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">6</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Bank Levy w</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">as introduced in Finance Act 2011 and the Government committed to undertake a review in 2013.   The review of the Bank Levy commenced shortly after most banks had submitted their first returns under the tax and accordingly there was minimal appetite for ra</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">dical changes to the structure of the levy.   In some respects the timing of the review was unfortunate as there are a number of regulatory changes that may impact the Bank Levy methodology but these were not sufficiently advanced at the time of the consul</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">tation to inform legislative change.    However, the Government was committed to the original timetable and the consultation nevertheless served a useful purpose in confirming that the Levy was broadly operating effectively.   </span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6.5pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">7</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We believe the Bank Levy rev</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">iew was handled well by HMRC and whilst there are questions as to whether a review in 2013 was necessary it is a good example of the Government reviewing and evaluating a new tax.    The consultation itself did follow the stages one to three of the develop</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ment of tax policy (legislative changes were included in the 2014 Finance Bill and therefore remaining stages of consultation fall outside the period covered by this report).   Indeed it is encouraging that HMRC stated that they consulted informally to inf</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">orm the content of the consultation exercise.   Although this pre-consultation was not widely publicised, it is nevertheless a welcome pre-curser to a formal consultation exercise</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6.5pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">8</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The one criticism is that the changes announced at the 2013 Autumn Statement were cast in terms of a broadening of the Bank Levy base.   If this was the policy intention this was not made clear as part of the consultation process.  </span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6.5pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">9</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The most contentious el</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ement of this consultation was a proposal to reinforce an entirely voluntary Code of Practice with a statutory regime for “naming and shaming” institutions that were considered by HMRC to be non-compliant.   This raised real issues as to how the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">administra</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">tion of the UK tax system is perceived by international investors  and we believe these important policy considerations were not given adequate attention as part of the consultation process.   </span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6.5pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">10</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Having said this, the consultation process did ensure that som</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e safe-guards against unwarranted “naming and shaming” by HMRC were ultimate included in the draft Finance Bill clauses.   Whilst we believe the Finance Bill legislation will still play badly with international investors the outcome was improved by consult</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ation.    However, some of the reputational damage could have been mitigated had the original policy objectives been subject to consultation in advance of HMRC releasing draft legislation.   We recommend therefore that where proposals are likely to be cont</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">entious that there is a separation between stage two and three of the consultation process.    </span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6.5pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Corporate debt and derivative contracts</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6.5pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">11</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> consultation on modernising the taxation of corporate debt and derivative contracts was viewed by us as partly follo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">wing the new policy. The overall timetable for the consultation and implementation of changes could have been much better managed. A lengthy 109 page consultation document was released over the summer and request for responses requested by the end of Augus</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">t, which did not allow sufficient time for business to provide a full and proper response.</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6.5pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">12</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The timetable of the changes being proposed in two tranches i.e. in Finance Bill 2014 and Finance Bill 2015 will mean that the bulk of the regime changes will take e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ffect from 1 January 2016 with some changes proposed to be introduced early in piecemeal fashion. Most groups (with calendar year ends) will have to deal with UK GAAP transition for year commencing 1 January 2015. This means that there will likely be inter</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">im measures required by regulation for the year end 31 December 2015, until the new regime takes effect – whilst this is necessary, it will add some complexity and uncertainty. In addition groups will have to manage two very complex transitions in the spac</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e of 2 years. Given these factors and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> intention to include some clauses in Finance Bill 2014, the consultation process should have been started 12-24 months earlier</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">or possibly delayed</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6.5pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">13</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Subsequent to the release of the consultation document, we welcome the approach </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">adopted</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> by HMRC to the ongoing consultation discussions, which have been professional, constructive and undertaken in an open and cooperative manner. HMRC seem keen to understa</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">nd instances where potential proposals may cause problems for business, meeting an objective of the new approach to policy making. In some instances, HMRC have come to sensible conclusions despite internal pressures.</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6.5pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Statutory residence test</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6.5pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">14</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Another exampl</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e where the new approach was followed in part was the statutory residence test consultation.  The new approach was successfully followed until the legislation was subject to last minute changes after the Finance Bill was published – namely the split year r</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ules and the meaning of working full time in the UK or overseas. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">These later additions are impractical and result in uncertainty which the statutory residence test hoped to avoid.</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6.5pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Real</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> Time Information</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6.5pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">15</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">An example where the policy was not followed was the R</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">eal Time Information consultation where HMRC and the Department for Work &amp; Pensions would not jointly consult with businesses. When consultation with business finally took place, HMRC said the “on or before” rule was </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">required</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> by the DWP and DWP said it was</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">required</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> by HMRC.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> The lack of consultation on the early design of the system is now causing extra burdens for businesses, HMRC and agents as HMRC’s Debt Management Teams chase “incorrect debts” without full sight of the data submitted. This will only be e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">xacerbated if the automatic issuing of penalties commences without these problems being addressed.</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6.5pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Partnership taxation</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6.5pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">16</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The partnership taxation changes are another example where the framework for tax policy making has not</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> been properly followed</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">This has</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> resulted in unclear legislation which requires a significant amount of guidance to interpret</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6.5pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6.5pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">I will submit further written evidence on this part of the call for evidence in a subsequent letter</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="Yours"></a><a name="ExtraSignOffText"></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">January 2014</span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt"><tr><td style="padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:219.4pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:9pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p></td><td style="padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:219.4pt"><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 2pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:9pt">1</span></p></td></tr></table><p style="margin:0pt; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:'Univers 45 Light'; font-size:1pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>